<meta name="twitter:description" content="The US Navy guided-missile destroyer USS Winston S. Churchill, part of Destroyer Squadron 2, anchors in Port Sudan on March 1, 2021. (Photo from AFP via Getty Images)


(CNSNews.com) - Following two U.S. Navy ship collisions in 2017, the Navy found that sailor overwork, fatigue, and training deficiencies contributed to the accidents, and while it has taken steps to address those issues, more needs to be done, the General Accountability Office says in a new report.

The GAO found that sailors still are not receiving adequate sleep.

Based on a survey in 2020, GAO estimates that only 14 percent of Navy officers received the then-recommended 7 hours or more of sleep a day during their most recent deployment, while 67 percent received 5 hours or less.

Navy data show that sailor effectiveness declines after prolonged periods without sleep, producing impairment levels comparable to intoxication.

The Navy updated its policy in December 2020, setting fatigue guidelines, but without &quot;quality information&quot; on the factors that cause lack of sleep, the Navy cannot effectively manage fatigue to ensure crews operate ships safely, GAO said.

The study also found that the Navy &quot;routinely assigns fewer crewmembers to its ships than its workload studies have determined are needed to safely operate them.&quot; This is because the Navy, until recently, tracked its crewing against the number of funded positions rather than against the number of required positions. (Although the Navy began tracking required positions in February 2021, this practice is not reflected in guidance.)

The Navy also uses funded positions, rather than required positions, to project its future personnel needs. &quot;Therefore,&quot; GAO said, &quot;it is not accurately communicating to internal decisionmakers the number of personnel it will need as the fleet grows, which may prevent it from effectively mitigating current crewing shortfalls.&quot;

GAO is making eight recommendations to the Navy, including that it revise its guidance and practices to measure sailor fatigue and address the factors causing fatigue; use required positions when reporting crew sizes and projecting personnel needs; and factor training time into sailor workload. DOD concurred with GAO’s recommendations.

GAO based its study on what it calls a &quot;generalizable sample of Navy officers&quot; who have dealt with the Navy&#039;s new fatigue management practices. The GAO also looked a ship crewing data for fiscal years 2017 through 2020. GAO also reviewed relevant Navy guidance, documentation, and interviewed relevant officials." />
